--- PART 4: Q_k(Paley) = 1/4 + p/4 = (p+1)/4 ---
Since D(k) = chi(k)*sqrt(p)/2, D^2 = p/4 for all k
=> Q_k = 1/4 + p/4 = (p+1)/4 for all k
This PROVES the flat Fourier spectrum from Gauss sum theory!

--- PART 5: WALSH-TO-GAUSS CONNECTION ---
h_hat[S] = (1/2^m) * sum_sigma H(sigma) * prod_{i in S} sigma_i
At sigma_Paley: prod_{i in S} sigma_i = prod_{i in S} chi(i+1) = chi(prod(i+1))
=> H(sigma_Paley) = sum_S h_hat[S] * chi(prod gaps in S)

The Sign Law says: h_hat[S] * chi(prod gaps in S) = |h_hat[S]|
i.e., every Walsh term is POSITIVE at sigma_Paley
=> H(sigma_Paley) = sum |h_hat[S]| >= sum h_hat[S]*prod(sigma) for any sigma

  p=7, m=3:
    S=(0, 1), deg=2, gaps=[1, 2], prod=2, chi=+1, h_hat=     +3.5000, sign=+1, match=Y
    S=(0, 2), deg=2, gaps=[1, 3], prod=3, chi=-1, h_hat=     -3.5000, sign=-1, match=Y
    S=(1, 2), deg=2, gaps=[2, 3], prod=6, chi=-1, h_hat=     -3.5000, sign=-1, match=Y
  Sign Law holds: True

